AGI - Since the avian influence has turned the eggs into a 'luxury bean', Annie Clemmons > has spent countless hours in her Maryland pastry laboratory to shake on how to replace them in her recipes. "It will not taste like chickpeas," assures while pouring the aquafaba>, the aqueous by-product of cooked legumes, in the bowl of its electric mixer.
<h2> A vegan recipe to replace eggs
A client ordered a red fruit pavlova > based on meringue and asked for it to be delivered on the same day. Instead of mounting snow albums, like in the traditional recipe, Clemmons uses a well-known alternative to vegan cooks and egg intolerants. "It takes a little more time," he says, "but there is no difference in color or taste." And for the pastry cream, use corn starch as a thickener. "It will not be so creamy", admits adding a spoon of cardamom to enhance its taste.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> Avian influence and impact on the market of eggs
The growing number of avian influenza outbreaks in U.S. farms made eggs a costly and rare commodity and so Clemmons sought ways to replace this essential ingredient in pastry. "I'm like gold," he said, showing the 20 eggs he still has in stock. "I never thought they'd be a luxury good."
Estimated that an egg that first cost 8 cents now costs 45, more than five times so.> After opening in 2020 the online bakery 'Chapman's DC', a confectionery delivery activity in the Washington metropolitan area, in the middle of the collapse of the activities in restaurants and hotels following the Covid-related pandemic, is now dealing with another unexpected crisis.
<h2> Surrogates and the uncertain future of eggs
"I have to think very carefully about when I use those eggs," he says. "I don't know when the next time I can use eggs without limits. Luckily, we have 'surrogates', but I really wish we could get the real eggs back soon."
<h2> Price slowdowns and market effects
The White House > has enthusiastically announced the third consecutive week of reduction of wholesale prices for standard eggs which, according to the Ministry of Agriculture, is the result both of slowing demand in front of high prices and of a truce of avian influence, which so far forced the breeders to break down over 30 million ovarian hens >. However, these calis still need to reflect on the shelves of shops. According to the consumer price index, eggs prices increased by more than 12% in February and by almost 59% compared to the previous year.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> Economic crisis and effects on Clemmons' business
But it's not just the egg crisis that weighs on the number of orders arriving at his store. The mass dismissals of federal employees by the new administration have undoubtedly hindered the question: "I live in the Washington DC area and a large part of my community has suffered a crisis. Losing your income, your work, your livelihood leads people to become more cautious in expenses."
<h2> Tariff policies and the threat to confectionery
But threatening US pastry is also the possible chain effects of Trump's tariff policies on another essential ingredient: sugar>. If sugar prices should increase sharply, Clemmons and many others may be forced to look for a new job.
